Concepts from [linear algebra](/Linear_algebra)

"Characteristic root" redirects here. For the root of a characteristic equation, see [Characteristic equation (calculus)](/Characteristic_equation_(calculus)).

In the vast, often tedious, landscape of [linear algebra](/Linear_algebra), an eigenvector (pronounced, for those still struggling with basic phonetics, [/ˈaɪɡən-/](/Help:IPA/English) EYE-gən- ) or characteristic vector emerges as a concept of fundamental, if somewhat unexciting, importance. At its core, an eigenvector is a (nonzero) [vector](/Vector_(mathematics_and_physics)) that possesses the peculiar quality of having its [direction](/Direction_(geometry)) utterly unchanged (or, for the sake of variety, merely reversed) when subjected to a specific [linear transformation](/Linear_map). To be more precise, and frankly, we *must* be precise here, an eigenvector




