Considering an [n-dimensional vector space](/Vector_space) and the arbitrary selection of a [basis](/Basis_(linear_algebra)), a direct and unambiguous correspondence exists between [linear transformations](/Linear_map) operating from the vector space onto itself and [n-by-n square matrices](/Square_matrix). This means that, within a [finite-dimensional vector space](/Vector_space), one can equivalently define eigenvalues and eigenvectors using either the abstract language of [linear transformations](/Linear_map) or the more concrete, computationally friendly language of [matrices](/Matrix_(mathematics)). It's two sides of the same coin, for those who appreciate such metaphors.

Overview

Eigenvalues and eigenvectors, as you might have gathered, loom rather prominently in the rigorous analysis of [linear transformations](/Linear_map). The prefix "eigen-," which so many find perplexing, is, in fact, merely adopted from the [German](/German_language) word *eigen*. This term is [cognate](/Cognate) with the [English](/English_language) word "own," and carries connotations of 'proper,' 'characteristic,' or 'intrinsic.' It implies a unique, inherent property, not merely something generic. Originally, these concepts were employed to dissect the [principal axes](/Principal_axis_(mechanics)) of the [rotational motion](/Rotation_(mathematics)) of [rigid bodies](/Rigid_body) – a problem of considerable practical importance, one would assume. Today, their applications are far-reaching and, frankly, rather predictable: they are found in [stability analysis](/Stability_theory), ensuring structures don't simply collapse; in [vibration analysis](/Vibration_analysis), determining how things oscillate; in the abstract world of [atomic orbitals](/Atomic_orbital), mapping electron behavior; in the surprisingly tangible realm of [facial recognition](/Eigenface), identifying individuals; and in the elegant process of [matrix diagonalization](/Eigendecomposition_of_a_matrix), simplifying complex systems.

At its core, an eigenvector v of a [linear transformation](/Linear_map) T is a nonzero vector that, upon T's application, maintains its original direction. The transformation simply scales the eigenvector by a [scalar](/Scalar_(mathematics)) value λ, which we call an eigenvalue. This fundamental condition is succinctly captured by the equation:




