The concepts of eigenvalues and eigenvectors give rise to an entire family of closely related mathematical ideas, all liberally adorned with the "eigen-" prefix, because mathematicians, like everyone else, enjoy a good naming convention:

*   The collective assembly of all eigenvectors of a [linear transformation](/Linear_map), each meticulously paired with its corresponding eigenvalue, is rather grandly termed the eigensystem of that transformation. It’s the complete set of intrinsic behaviors, if you will.
*   The collection of all eigenvectors of T that correspond to the *same* eigenvalue, augmented by the ever-present zero vector, forms what is known as an eigenspace, or the characteristic space of T associated with that specific eigenvalue. This space represents all possible "directions" that remain invariant for a given scaling factor.
*   Should a set of eigenvectors of T be so accommodating as to form a [basis](/Basis_(linear_algebra)) for the domain of T, then this particularly useful basis is elevated to the status of an eigenbasis. It's the ideal coordinate system for understanding the transformation.

History

Eigenvalues, despite their current omnipresence in [linear algebra](/Linear_algebra) and [matrix theory](/Matrix_(mathematics)) curricula, did not spring fully formed from a textbook. Historically, their genesis lies in the investigation of [quadratic forms](/Quadratic_form) and the often-frustrating realm of [differential equations](/Differential_equation). It seems humanity always finds a way to complicate things before simplifying them.

In the 18th century, the venerable [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler) embarked upon a detailed study of the [rotational motion](/Rotation_(mathematics)) of a [rigid body](/Rigid_body). It was in this context that he stumbled upon the profound significance of the [principal axes](/Moment_of_inertia) – those special axes around which a body rotates without wobble. A few decades later, [Joseph-Louis Lagrange](/Joseph-Louis_Lagrange) made the crucial realization that these very [principal axes](/Principal_axis_(mechanics)) were, in fact, the eigenvectors of the [inertia matrix](/Inertia_tensor) – a rather elegant connection between geometry and algebra.

The early 19th century witnessed [Augustin-Louis Cauchy](/Augustin-Louis_Cauchy) extending this work, recognizing its utility in classifying [quadric surfaces](/Quadric) and generalizing these insights to arbitrary dimensions. Cauchy, ever the innovator, also bestowed upon us the term *racine caractéristique* (characteristic root), the direct ancestor of our modern "eigenvalue," a term that, rather stubbornly, survives in the [characteristic equation](/Characteristic_polynomial).

Later, in 1822, [Joseph Fourier](/Joseph_Fourier), building upon the foundations laid by Lagrange and [Pierre-Simon Laplace](/Pierre-Simon_Laplace), leveraged these concepts to solve the notoriously difficult [heat equation](/Heat_equation) using the method of [separation of variables](/Separation_of_variables), as detailed in his seminal treatise, *[The Analytic Theory of Heat (Théorie analytique de la chaleur)](/Joseph_Fourier)*. [Charles-François Sturm](/Charles-Fran%C3%A7ois_Sturm) further refined Fourier's ideas, drawing them to Cauchy's attention. This collaboration led to the significant discovery that [real symmetric matrices](/Symmetric_matrix) invariably possess real eigenvalues – a property that simplifies many practical problems. This finding was subsequently broadened by [Charles Hermite](/Charles_Hermite) in 1855 to encompass what are now known as [Hermitian matrices](/Hermitian_matrix), which are, in essence, complex generalizations of symmetric matrices.

Around this same period, [Francesco Brioschi](/Francesco_Brioschi) demonstrated that the eigenvalues of [orthogonal matrices](/Orthogonal_matrix) always reside on the [unit circle](/Unit_circle) in the complex plane – a result indicating preservation of length. Concurrently, [Alfred Clebsch](/Alfred_Clebsch) elucidated the analogous result for [skew-symmetric matrices](/Skew-symmetric_matrix). Finally, [Karl Weierstrass](/Karl_Weierstrass), in his contributions to [stability theory](/Stability_theory) (a field initiated by Laplace), highlighted a critical point: [defective matrices](/Defective_matrix), those lacking a full set of linearly independent eigenvectors, could lead to system instability, a rather inconvenient truth.

Meanwhile, [Joseph Liouville](/Joseph_Liouville) delved into eigenvalue problems strikingly similar to Sturm's, giving birth to the field now recognized as [Sturm–Liouville theory](/Sturm%E2%80%93Liouville_theory), a cornerstone of applied mathematics. Towards the close of the 19th century, [Hermann Schwarz](/Hermann_Schwarz) meticulously studied the first eigenvalue of [Laplace's equation](/Laplace%27s_equation) across various domains, while [Henri Poincaré](/Henri_Poincar%C3%A9) investigated [Poisson's equation](/Poisson%27s_equation) a few years later. It seems everyone wanted a piece of the eigenvalue pie.

The dawn of the 20th century saw [David Hilbert](/David_Hilbert) extending these concepts to the eigenvalues of [integral operators](/Integral_operator), conceptualizing these operators as infinite-dimensional matrices. Hilbert, in 1904, was the first to explicitly employ the [German](/German_language) word *eigen*, meaning "own" or "characteristic," to designate eigenvalues and eigenvectors, though he might have been influenced by a similar usage from [Hermann von Helmholtz](/Hermann_von_Helmholtz). For a time, the accepted English term was "proper value," but the more distinctive, and frankly, less ambiguous, "eigenvalue" has since become the standard. A small victory for clarity, perhaps.

The quest for practical methods to compute these values led to significant advancements. The first numerical algorithm for calculating eigenvalues and eigenvectors emerged in 1929, when [Richard von Mises](/Richard_von_Mises) unveiled the [power method](/Power_method), a relatively simple iterative technique. Fast forward to 1961, and two independent breakthroughs occurred: [John G. F. Francis](/John_G._F._Francis) and [Vera Kublanovskaya](/Vera_Kublanovskaya) each proposed the [QR algorithm](/QR_algorithm), which remains one of the most widely used and efficient methods today. It seems even the most abstract concepts eventually require a calculator.

Eigenvalues and eigenvectors of matrices

*   See also: [Euclidean vector](/Euclidean_vector) and [Matrix (mathematics)](/Matrix_(mathematics))

Eigenvalues and eigenvectors are, rather predictably, often introduced to students within the confines of [linear algebra](/Linear_algebra) courses, where the focus invariably gravitates towards [matrices](/Matrix_(mathematics)). This is not without reason. Furthermore, [linear transformations](/Linear_map) operating over a [finite-dimensional vector space](/Vector_space) can be quite conveniently represented using [matrices](/Matrix_(mathematics)). This representation becomes particularly dominant and useful in [numerical](/Numerical_analysis) and [computational applications](/Computational_mathematics), where abstract concepts need to be translated into something a machine can process.

