It's a common misconception that if the entries of [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) A are all [real numbers](/Real_number), then its eigenvalues must also be real. While the [coefficients](/Coefficient) of the [characteristic polynomial](/Characteristic_polynomial) will indeed be real, the eigenvalues themselves may very well possess nonzero [imaginary parts](/Imaginary_unit) – a fact that often surprises those new to the field. Consequently, the entries of the corresponding eigenvectors may also be [complex numbers](/Complex_number). Similarly, eigenvalues can be [irrational numbers](/Irrational_number) even if all entries of A are [rational numbers](/Rational_number), or even integers. However, a small comfort: if all entries of A are [algebraic numbers](/Algebraic_number) (which includes all rationals), then the eigenvalues are guaranteed to be [algebraic numbers](/Algebraic_number) as well.

A salient feature of polynomials with real [coefficients](/Coefficient) is that their non-real roots always manifest in pairs of [complex conjugates](/Complex_conjugate). This means that for each complex eigenvalue, its conjugate will also be an eigenvalue, with their imaginary parts differing only in sign while sharing the same real part. Furthermore, if the polynomial's degree is odd, the [intermediate value theorem](/Intermediate_value_theorem) guarantees that at least one of its roots must be real. Therefore, any [real matrix](/Real_matrix) with an odd order (e.g., 3x3, 5x5) will necessarily possess at least one real eigenvalue. Conversely, a [real matrix](/Real_matrix) of even order (e.g., 2x2, 4x4) might, in its infinite capacity for mischief, have no real eigenvalues at all. The eigenvectors associated with these complex eigenvalues are, predictably, also complex and, much like their eigenvalues, appear in complex conjugate pairs.

Spectrum of a matrix

The [spectrum](/Spectrum_of_a_matrix) of a [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) is not some grand celestial phenomenon, but rather the complete list of its eigenvalues, with each eigenvalue repeated according to its [multiplicity](/Multiple_roots_of_a_polynomial). In an alternative, slightly more formal notation, it is the set of eigenvalues along with their respective multiplicities. It’s a comprehensive inventory of a matrix's intrinsic scaling factors.

An important quantity derived from this spectrum is the maximum absolute value among all eigenvalues. This is rather grandly known as the [spectral radius](/Spectral_radius) of the matrix. It often dictates the convergence properties and long-term behavior of systems described by the matrix.

Algebraic multiplicity

Let λ i denote an eigenvalue of an [n-by-n matrix](/Square_matrix) A. The algebraic multiplicity, denoted as μ A ( λ i ), of this eigenvalue is defined as its [multiplicity as a root](/Multiple_roots_of_a_polynomial) of the [characteristic polynomial](/Characteristic_polynomial). More precisely, it is the largest integer k such that ( λ − λ i ) k [evenly divides](/Polynomial_division) that polynomial. This tells us how "many times" an eigenvalue appears as a root.

