Because the eigenspace E holds the distinguished status of being a [linear subspace](/Linear_subspace), it exhibits the property of being [closed](/Closure_(mathematics)) under vector addition. This means that if any two vectors u and v belong to the set E (denoted as u , v ∈ E ), then their sum, u + v, will also reside within E. This can be verified by applying the [distributive property](/Distributive_property) of [matrix multiplication](/Matrix_multiplication): A(u+v) = Au + Av = λu + λv = λ(u+v). Similarly, due to its nature as a [linear subspace](/Linear_subspace), E is also [closed](/Closure_(mathematics)) under [scalar multiplication](/Scalar_multiplication). If v ∈ E and α is a [complex number](/Complex_number), then α v ∈ E. This is straightforwardly confirmed by noting the [commutative property](/Commutative_property) of [scalar multiplication](/Scalar_multiplication) with [complex matrices](/Complex_number): A(αv) = α(Av) = α(λv) = λ(αv). As long as u + v and α v do not happen to be the zero vector, they too are eigenvectors of A associated with λ, demonstrating the linear structure of these "invariant directions."

