*   If A is equal to its [conjugate transpose](/Conjugate_transpose) A ∗ (or, equivalently, if A is a [Hermitian matrix](/Hermitian_matrix)), then every single eigenvalue is guaranteed to be a real number. The same holds true for any [symmetric](/Symmetric_matrix) real matrix, a special case of a Hermitian matrix. This is a remarkably useful property in physics and engineering.
*   If A is not only [Hermitian](/Hermitian_matrix) but also [positive-definite](/Positive-definite_matrix), then all its eigenvalues are strictly positive. If it's positive-semidefinite, they are non-negative. Conversely, for negative-definite and negative-semidefinite matrices, the eigenvalues are strictly negative or non-positive, respectively. These properties are crucial for understanding the "energy" or "definiteness" of a system.
*   If A is a [unitary matrix](/Unitary_matrix), a transformation that preserves inner products (and thus lengths), then every eigenvalue λ i has an absolute value of 1 (&#124; λ i &#124; = 1). This means they lie on the [unit circle](/Unit_circle) in the complex plane, indicating a rotational or reflective action.
*   More generally, if A is an n × n [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) and { λ 1 , ... , λ k } are its eigenvalues, then the eigenvalues of the matrix I + A (where I is the [identity matrix](/Identity_matrix)) are simply { λ 1 + 1, ... , λ k + 1}. Even more broadly, if



