This process, where A is broken down into a matrix of its eigenvectors, a [diagonal matrix](/Diagonal_matrix) containing its eigenvalues, and the inverse of the eigenvector matrix, is known as the [eigendecomposition](/Eigendecomposition). It is, in essence, a [similarity transformation](/Matrix_similarity). A [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) A that can be subjected to this process is said to be similar to the [diagonal matrix](/Diagonal_matrix) Λ, or, more simply, [diagonalizable](/Diagonalizable_matrix). The matrix Q, in this context, serves as the change of basis matrix for the [similarity transformation](/Matrix_similarity). Fundamentally, matrices A and Λ represent the identical [linear transformation](/Linear_map), but expressed within two distinct bases. The eigenvectors themselves are utilized as the basis when the [linear transformation](/Linear_map) is represented by Λ, which is often a far simpler form to work with.

Conversely, imagine a [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) A that is known to be [diagonalizable](/Diagonalizable_matrix). This implies there exists a non-singular [square matrix](/Square_matrix) P such that P −1 AP results in some [diagonal matrix](/Diagonal_matrix) D. If we left-multiply both sides of this expression by P, we get AP = PD. From this, it follows that each column of P must be an eigenvector of A, with its corresponding eigenvalue being the diagonal element from D in the same column. Since the columns of P must be [linearly independent](/Linear_independence) for P to be invertible, we can conclude that there exist n [linearly independent](/Linear_independence) eigenvectors of A. This leads to a crucial insight: the eigenvectors of A form a [basis](/Basis_(linear_algebra)) for the vector space if and only if A is [diagonalizable](/Diagonalizable_matrix).

A [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) that stubbornly refuses to be [diagonalizable](/Diagonalizable_matrix) is termed a [defective matrix](/Defective_matrix). For these less cooperative matrices, the straightforward notion of eigenvectors must be generalized to [generalized eigenvectors](/Generalized_eigenvector), and the elegant [diagonal matrix](/Diagonal_matrix) of eigenvalues expands into the more complex, but still structured, [Jordan normal form](/Jordan_normal_form). Over an [algebraically closed field](/Algebraically_closed_field), such as the [complex numbers](/Complex_number), any [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) A is guaranteed to possess a [Jordan normal form](/Jordan_normal_form). This means it admits a basis composed of [generalized eigenvectors](/Generalized_eigenvector) and a decomposition into [generalized eigenspaces](/Generalized_eigenspace), ensuring that even the "defective" matrices can be understood, albeit with a bit more effort.

Variational characterization

*   Main article: [Min-max theorem](/Min-max_theorem)

In the specific realm of [Hermitian matrices](/Hermitian_matrix) (which include [symmetric real matrices](/Symmetric_matrix) as a special case), eigenvalues are not merely roots of a polynomial; they can be given a powerful variational characterization. The largest eigenvalue of a Hermitian matrix H, for instance, corresponds to the maximum value that the [quadratic form](/Quadratic_form) x T H x / x T x can attain. Furthermore, any vector x that actually achieves this maximum value is, by definition, an eigenvector of H. This principle is formally captured by the [Min-max theorem](/Min-max_theorem), a cornerstone of spectral theory for these matrices. It provides a way to "feel out" the eigenvalues by probing the matrix's action on vectors.

